snippet.textDisplay: Just a thought, but if the weight of all the trash is what makes it impossibly expensive to launch it off of Earth, why not build a massive incinerator and set up capture pipes to feed it into large lightweight but sturdy Hollow sealed containers? That way all the harmful gases and CFCs and particles associated with open-air incineration would instead be safely sequestered. Those barrels could then be loaded into cheaply made one time use Rockets and would all but eliminate the weight issue that makes it so difficult to leave Earth's gravity well. some of those fumes and gases may even be able to be used, at least in part, as a source of fuel. And why not launch it all into our largest gas giant, Jupiter? It's a lot easier to move things away from the Sun then towards it and Jupiter already serves as our solar systems vacuum cleaner. Anything we launch at it will be pulled into its massive gravity well and reduced to its Elementary particles by the volatile environment of Jupiter's atmosphere. We already disposed of a spent nuclear powered probe within the atmosphere of Saturn, and it seems no worse for the wear.

snippet.textDisplay:
I doubt we'll ever get the capability to transfer all our trash to the sun, which is kinda like someone saying in 1893 that they doubted we'll ever achieve heavier-than-air flight. It was kinda impossible when steam engines were "the" available engines; it took the invention of internal combustion engines -- smaller and lighter for the same power — before flight was possible. And the Wrights didn't fully understand the forces involved; NO one else understood them much as well as they did. The Wright flyer was dangerous to fly; crashed at the end of the first day, I believe. These days, a quite safe plane, called a "Quickie", can be home-built to fly LONG distances safely with the modern equivalent of the Wright Flyer's 12 Hp, perhaps even the self-same one; I dunno, I haven't looked up anything.
Perhaps in the near future, we'll invent/discover a better propulsive technique or a wormhole directly to the Sun or some other "cheat" which will make it possible. Then we get to ponder the question: Given that we can throw our trash into the Sun, SHOULD we? I believe we SHOULDN'T until and unless we understand all of the ramifications.

snippet.textDisplay:
Short answer: we can't cause it's really expensive.

Long answer: it currently costs around $10,000 per kilogram to get something into orbit. As we have collected millions of kilos of waste over the years, it isn't realistic in any monetary world. The bigger issue, the amount of energy it would take to accomplish this task outside of a monetary world would be beyond the upper limits of our possible energy output. Moreover, we won't have enough energy until we achieve the limits of a 1st level civilization. Currently we haven't even reached that level. We are still are level 0 civilization.

We can have a Stargate on Venus and transport our garbage there. The ~450 Celsius surface temperature will deal with whatever we put there. It’s not like the Venusian surface could harbor life or be otherwise useful. We can’t have a Stargate orbiting the sun, as it is common knowledge that a slight solar flare would cause massive time traveling issues. Mercury is also ruled out for the same reason due to its proximity to the sun. So, problem solved! Just one thing...

snippet.textDisplay:
Seems like this is making a couple bad assumptions. Like, they're comparing it to launching manned rockets and scientific probes. Really important stuff that requires a lot of effort to not only get it where it's going but make sure the contents don't die/break. This is trash. We wouldn't about damage to the contents beyond making sure the container doesn't break open and spill the trash into Earth orbit. So am I missing something, or wouldn't this look less like a space shuttle launch and more like building a really big cannon to shoot stuff in space towards the general direction of away?

That still might not be practical, but not sure how much the cost of existing methods and infrastructure are applicable here.

Didn't know all that stuff about orbital mechanics making it harder to fire something at the sun. But that just means you'd want to substitute Jupiter.
